doctype html

//- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
//- AngularJS 1.5.10 -> React 18 coexistence route cutover (Blitzy AAP 0.2.1 /
//- 0.4.1). The Kanban board previously rendered by the AngularJS kanban
//- controller (and its tgKanban / tgKanbanSwimlane / tgKanbanWipLimit
//- directives, plus the kanban-table partial and the create/edit + bulk-create
//- lightboxes) is now rendered in place by the <tg-react-kanban> custom element.
//- React 18 owns everything INSIDE that tag: connectedCallback mounts a React
//- root and renders the board (columns, swimlanes, WIP limits, sidebar filters,
//- zoom, and the lightboxes), reproducing the same DOM structure and CSS class
//- names so the existing SCSS styles the React output unchanged.
//-
//- HOW THE ELEMENT IS LIVE: <tg-react-kanban> is registered (customElements.define)
//- by the react.js bundle, which app-loader/app-loader.coffee loads BETWEEN
//- elements.js and app.js -- i.e. before angular.bootstrap(document, ['taiga']).
//- Because the element is already defined when AngularJS $compile first
//- encounters this template, AngularJS treats it as an ordinary custom element
//- and passes its internals through inertly: React owns everything INSIDE the
//- tag while AngularJS owns the navigation chrome OUTSIDE it. This re-applies the
//- coexistence pattern the repository already ships for its Angular-Elements
//- bundle (tg-main / tg-navigation-bar / tg-live-announcement in app/index.jade).
//-
//- CHROME OUTSIDE THE BOUNDARY: the project archived-warning banner and the left
//- tg-project-menu sidebar are self-contained AngularJS components (driven by the
//- shared project service and the route's `section` property, not by the former
//- controller), so they remain here as siblings. React's createRoot wipes the
//- host element's children, so the menu must be a sibling of -- not a child of --
//- the custom element. The `.wrapper` flex row (display:flex; height:100%, see
//- app/styles/core/base.scss) lays the project menu beside the board exactly as
//- before, and ng-init sets the `section` scope variable the menu reads to
//- highlight the active screen.
//-
//- NO project-slug ATTRIBUTE is passed on purpose: TgReactKanban resolves the
//- slug as getAttribute('project-slug') ?? getProjectSlug(), so it only falls
//- back to the reliable URL (/project/:pslug/kanban) when the attribute is
//- ABSENT; an AngularJS-interpolated {{project.slug}} would be an empty string at
//- mount time and would suppress that fallback.
//-
//- The inline flex style reproduces the `.main { flex: 1; min-width: 0 }` rule on
//- the host tag so the React board occupies the exact same width the AngularJS
//- section.main did, beside the fixed-width project menu -- keeping the layout
//- pixel-identical without editing any stylesheet. KanbanApp itself renders the
//- board shell (`.wrapper > section.main.kanban`, header, filters, zoom,
//- swimlanes, columns/cards) and its own create/edit + bulk lightboxes.
//-
//- SCOPE NOTE: only the ROUTE-LEVEL rendering is superseded here. The AngularJS
//- taigaKanban module registration is deliberately RETAINED elsewhere because the
//- out-of-scope taskboard screen registers services onto it; those legacy
//- controllers/directives simply become unreachable dead code on this route.
//- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

//- AngularJS chrome -- stays OUTSIDE the React boundary.
tg-project-archived-warning

div.wrapper(ng-init="section='kanban'")
    //- AngularJS navigation sidebar -- chrome, OUTSIDE the React boundary.
    tg-project-menu

    //- React Kanban board host. The inline flex style makes the host occupy the
    //- exact width the former section.main did (flex:1; min-width:0), beside the
    //- fixed-width project menu. No project-slug attribute is passed (see above).
    tg-react-kanban(style="flex: 1 1 0%; min-width: 0;")
